title: For Sale:  1933 ex-PE sniper Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
I don't need to sell it, I just don't ever get around to shooting it. 

It is a 1933 Tula ex-PE sniper, hex receiver. I have had the bolt turned down to the proper configuration. It also has a "smith sights" adjustable front sight post, as well as a jmeck low profile no gunsmith clamp on scope mount currently with a Bushnell Banner CF500 scope on it. Reproduction sling as well, and about 70rds of surplus ammo. 1933 was the first year sniper rifles were specifically produced however they did not mark them as such until 1934. So there is no steel stamp marking identifying it as a "sniper" rifle, however the PE mounting holes are there, albeit plugged from the rearsenal process. I can send pics of them on request as some disassembly is required to see them well. This rifle has not been counter bored either and is in overall great shape! This stock is in great shape as well!

You can purchase a reproduction PE scope and mount from accumounts for a period correct setup but that was a little more than I was willing to spend, and more work (drilling out welds) than I was up for!

Asking $400

title: For Sale:  .308 (7.62x51) Practice Ammo - CHEAP
postcontent:
Selling the last of my .308 (7.62x51) training ammo that I purchased awhile back. I have since sold my .308 rifle and no longer have a need for this ammo. I shot well over 1,000 rounds of this stuff when had my .308, and it is a blast to shoot...and very cheap as well compared to traditional .308 ammo.

Made in Germany and designed for Military live fire training exercises. The FBI still uses it to this day as well.

It is an all plastic round (except the primer) that is the same dimensions as a traditional .308 round.  It's accurate enough out to about 200yds with an approx/average muzzle velocity of 4,400fps @ 472 ft-lbs of energy pushing a 10gr projectile. Pretty crazy huh?

YouTube video of this same exact ammo: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DnEdwZv9WsU 

I have personally shot this stuff through 3/4" plywood at well over 100 yards and it just punches right threw it like nothing. That said, this stuff IS NOT A TOY. IT IS LETHAL at considerable distances.

I have approx 900 rounds remaining. Most of which is still factory sealed. 

Price is $150 for all 900 rounds. Will not separate. Must be 18 with a valid ID. No Shipping. CCW preferred. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  FOR SALE: RARE STINGER PEN PISTOL GUN .22LR R.J. BRAVERMAN
postcontent:
This interesting piece looks like a pen but transforms in seconds into a working legal pistol. Most "pen guns" fall into the legal category of "any other weapon," and as such, must be registered. R.J. Braverman’s Stinger Pen Pistols, however, must be folded into a gun-like shape before firing, earning them a Title I designation from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms, and Explosives (Title I firearms are just ordinary guns with no additional regulations imposed upon them).
These little pistols were produced in the early 1990’s and were chambered for .22 LR Rimfire, .22 Magnum Rimfire, .25 ACP, .32 ACP, and .380 ACP ammunition. They were just over 5 1/2 inches in length with a 2 inch barrel when folded. This pen gun has only been shot once it is like new 22cal. If you live in Connecticut we can fill out the necessary forms must have Connecticut Pistol Permit. All other will have to go though your and mine gun dealer to ship. 

While it is estimated that only around 4,000 R.J. Braverman Stinger Pen Pistols were made!!!!

title: For Sale:  WWII Japanese Army Officer’s Katana Samurai Sword by Kanewaka
postcontent: Both handles (Tsuka) will be shipped with the sword at the end of the auction; no matter of the price. The maker is Kanewaka per Slough's book on page 72. The other kanji is the date, with the Showa era stamp above it (from 1937-1945). In good overall condition, it measures approx 38-1/2” overall with a blade length of 25-5/8” and scabbard approx 28-3/4”. The wrapped handle (Tsuka) over white ray skin with unusual Menuki on both sides. The Pommel (Kashira (頭?), on the end of the handle (Tsuka) is missing and wrap is not tied on end. I do have a second handle in the pictures that will go with this auction. So you get two handles with the sword. The blade does show age graying and nicks-Temper line is there but faint. The (rayskin) Same-kawa (samegawa) (鮫皮?); on the scabbard (Saya (鞘?) is in very good condition; you can slide off the rayskin cover and see a black lacquered scabbard that is made in two pieces. The Tsuba is plain and appears to be made of iron. I purchased this katana at a military auction a couple of years ago and have lost interest in Japanese Military items.
